  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Provide framework for national anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n\n2. Compliance and Standardization\n- Countries develop national laws aligned with international standards\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering\n- Shared reporting and investigation protocols\n- Cross-border cooperation mechanisms\n\n3. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Treaties enabling information sharing\n- Joint investigations\n- Extradition of suspects\n- Asset recovery and freezing\n\n4. Regulatory Coordination\n- International financial institutions' oversight\n- Banks and financial entities required to implement global AML standards\n- Reporting suspicious transactions\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n\n5. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Sanctions for non-compliance\n- International monitoring\n- Peer review processes\n- Potential economic consequences for inadequate AML frameworks\n\n6. Technological Challenges\n- Addressing cryptocurrency and digital financial transactions\n- Adapting legal frameworks to evolving technologies\n- Collaborative approaches to emerging financial crime risks\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to combating money laundering globally.",
